<DOC><DOCNO> AP900101-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-01-90 0204EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Cold     01-01 0213</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Cold,0218</SECOND><HEAD>Eight More Cold Deaths Pushes Two-Week Toll to 60</HEAD><DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eight more people have died of exposureto the chilly weather gripping northern Bangladesh, bringing thedeath toll from the cold snap to 60 in two weeks, newspapers saidtoday.   In neighboring India, at least 61 people have died ofhypothermia in the same period.   Itefaq, an independent Dhaka daily, said six people died Sundayin the Panchagarh district where temperatures dropped to 36degrees, the lowest in three decades. Two people died of the coldin Jaipurhat district, according to Sangbad, another independentBengali-language newspaper.   Most of the cold wave victims had no homes and were sleeping onthe ground.   In Panchagarh, 220 miles north of Dhaka, the Bangladesh RedCrescent Society, the Moslem equivalent of the Red Cross, said itwas distributing warm clothing and blankets to poor people to helpthem cope with the cold.   Winter lows in northern Bangladesh usually hover around 44degrees.   The cold weather strikes hard at this country where the percapita annual income is $160 and even people with shelter areill-prepared for winter. Most houses in Bangladesh, a country of110 million people, have mud floors with walls fashioned from thinmats of straw or split bamboo.</TEXT></DOC>